\series bold
insolvent
\series default
 firms aren't solvent.
 
\series bold
Illiquid
\series default
 firms can't sell off their positions quickly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
National savings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
National savings
\series default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $S=I=Y-C-G$
\end_inset

.
 It is the amount of income a closed economy has invested back into itself.
 You can also think of it as the sum of 
\series bold
private savings
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y-T-C$
\end_inset

, and 
\series bold
public savings
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T-G$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 includes transfer payments because those count as public spending (???).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The loanable funds market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename econ102/circular-flow-plus-loanable-funds.png
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We add a bunch of green lines to show debt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: Household income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

: Household spending
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

: Household saving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

: Household net taxes (taxes paid less benefits received).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Y & =C+S+T
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By combining this with GDP, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=S+(T-G)+(M-X)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T-G$
\end_inset

 is the government budget surplus and 
\begin_inset Formula $(M-X)$
