\begin_layout Subsubsection
Interest rates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Nominal
\series default
 is before adjusting for inflation; 
\series bold
real
\series default
 is after.
 Interest rates in this section are generally real.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Supply and demand of loans
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher the interest rate, the more supply and the less demand there
 is for loanable funds.
 These are represented in two curves, 
\series bold
DLF
\series default
 (demand for loanable funds) and 
\series bold
SLF
\series default
 (supply of loanable funds).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantity of loanable funds supplied increases when:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The real interest rate
\series default
 is higher
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households have 
\series bold
more disposable income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households have 
\series bold
less expected future income
\series default
 (since they'll save more)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households have 
\series bold
less wealth
\series default
 (because people see more need to save)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Default risk is lower
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand for loanable funds increases when:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The real interest rate is higher
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The expected profit is higher
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this way, the interest rate is regulated by the supply and demand for
 loans.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename econ102/supply-and-demand-loans.png
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Effect of government
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
budget surplus
\series default
 increases the supply, which decreases the interest rate and the private
 supply (
\series bold
PSLF
\series default
) and increases private demand (
\series bold
PDLF
\series default
).
 A 
\series bold
budget deficit
\series default
 increases the demand, which increases the interest rate and the amount
 of private supply but decreases private demand (the 
\series bold
crowding-out effect
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
vicious cycle
\series default
 happens when government deficits reduce SLF, increasing interest rates,
 discouraging investments, slowing economic growth, lowering tax revenue,
 increasing deficits.
 The opposite happens with a surplus that we call a 
\series bold
virtuous cycle
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Ricardo-Barro effect
\series default
 says that government budget doesn't actually affect the interest rate,
 because rational taxpayers save more.
 Most economists find this interesting but extreme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Money (ch24)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Money
\series default
 is a 
\series bold
generally acceptable means of payment
\series default
 that overcomes the requirement for a 
\series bold
double coincidence of wants
\series default
 as occurs in 
\series bold
barter
\series default
.
 It is also:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a 
\series bold
medium of exchange
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a 
\series bold
unit of account
\series default
 (unit of measurement for prices)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a 
\series bold
store of value
\series default
 (carries purchasing power forward through time)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Money today is mostly in the form of 
\series bold
currency
\series default
 and 
\series bold
deposits
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two kinds of money: 
\series bold
commodity money
\series default
 (e.g.
 gold, cigarettes) and 
\series bold
fiat money
\series default
 (valuable only by government decree)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canada has two measures of the money stock: 
\series bold
M1
\series default
, which includes currency and chequable deposits and 
\series bold
M2
\series default
 which additionally includes non-chequable deposits and fixed term deposits.
 Stuff the government owns is not considered money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stuff that 
\series bold
isn't money
\series default
 by our definition: cheques, credit cards.
 They're just means of payment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Depository institutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three depository institutions make up Canada's money: 
\series bold
chartered banks
\series default
 such as RBC, CIBC, and BMO; 
\series bold
credit unions
\series default
, and 
\series bold
trust/mortgage loan companies
\series default
.
 We will call all these things 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

banks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chartered banks use their funds for four types of assets: 
\series bold
reserves
\series default
 of about 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5-1\%$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold
liquid assets
\series default
 such as treasury bills, 
\series bold
securities
\series default
 such as bonds, and 
\series bold
loans
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Banks provide these benefits:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Create liquidity
\series default
: they borrow short and lend long
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Pool risk
\series default
: one default doesn't have that big of an effect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Lower cost of borrowing
\series default
: by acting as a central counterparty (cpty)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Lower cost of monitoring borrowers
\series default
: by doing it efficiently
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is all 
\series bold
fractional reserve banking
\series default
, which is risky but don't worry, the CDIC insures $100k per depositor.
 And 
\series bold
Basel III
\series default
 will keep it from going that badly so we don't need 
\series bold
100 percent reserve banking
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Financial innovation
\series default
 is when banks create things like variable-rate mortgages and sell mortgage-back
ed securities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Bank of Canada
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is our 
\series bold
central bank
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It as a bank to banks and the government.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is a 
\series bold
lender of last resort
\series default
, for when the whole banking system is short of reserves.
 Banks borrow from each other at the 
\series bold
overnight rate
\series default
 and from the central bank at the 
\series bold
bank rate
\series default
.
 Assets in the central bank grow at the 
\series bold
settlement rate
\series default
 (currently bank rate less 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\%$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{bank rate}>\text{overnight rate}>\text{settlement rate}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is the 
\series bold
sole issuer of bank notes
\series default
, and so controls the monetary stock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Its 
\series bold
two assets 
\series default
are: government securities, and loans to banks (in times of crisis).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Its 
\series bold
two liabilities
\series default
: Bank of Canada notes (dollar bills!), bank deposits, and government deposits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our 
\series bold
monetary base
\series default
 is made up of the Bank of Canada's liabilities and the coins issued by
 the Royal Canadian Mint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Controlling the money supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bank of Canada can influence the money supply in the following ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perform an 
\series bold
open market operation
\series default
: trades government securities on the public market.
 Buying bonds increases, and selling bonds decreases, the money supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Change the 
\series bold
overnight rate
\series default
: It's always 
\begin_inset Formula $0.25\%$
\end_inset

 less than the bank rate.
 Increasing this rate stops banks from creating too much money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Changing reserve requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can also do forex market operations: buying foreign currency increases,
 and selling foreign currency decreases, the money supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sterilization
\series default
 is offsetting forex operations with open-market operations to cancel out
 the effect on the money supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creating money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Banks create money by making loans.
 This created money is limited by the monetary base, and further limited
 by the bank's 
\series bold
desired reserves
\series default
 (reserves that it plans to hold) and the 
\series bold
desired currency holding
\series default
.
 The 
\series bold
currency drain 
\series default
ratio
\series bold
 
\series default
is the ratio of currency to deposits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The banking system creates money as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The monetary base is increased.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bank reserves are increased, creating excess reserves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Banks lend out their excess reserves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The quantity of money increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
New deposits are used to make payments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Some money is lost through currency drain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The increase in deposits increase desired reserves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Banks have less excess reserves than before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
money multiplier
\series default
 gives the amount of money created by a change in the monetary base.
 In a simple case, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\text{reserve ratio}$
\end_inset

.
 In Canada, the M1 multiplier is about 
\begin_inset Formula $8\pm2$
\end_inset

 and the M2 multiplier is about 
\begin_inset Formula $18\pm2$
\end_inset

.
 It is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
mm & =M/MB\\
 & =(C+D)/(C+R)\\
 & =(1+C/D)/(R/D+C/D)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the amount of money, 
\begin_inset Formula $MB$
\end_inset

 is the monetary base, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is currency, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is deposits, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is bank reserves.
 (This means 
\begin_inset Formula $C/D$
\end_inset

 is the currency drain ratio and 
\begin_inset Formula $R/D$
\end_inset

 is the reserve ratio.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The money market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
quantity of money demanded
\series default
 is the amount we want to hold on to.
 It is influenced by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Price level: The more expensive things are, the more money we hold onto
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Nominal interest rate: The more we can make by investing, the less money
 we hold onto
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Real GDP: The more we spend, the more we must have held onto
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Financial innovation: More convenient means of payment that don't count
 as money means we hold onto less money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
demand for money
\series default
 is the demand curve between real money demanded and the nominal interest
 rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Short-run equilibrium
\series default
: The 
\series bold
supply of money curve
\series default
 is a vertical line at the supply of real money.
 Their intersection gives you the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equilibrium
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Long-run equilibrium
\series default
: When the inflation rate is as expected and real GDP equals potential GDP,
 the price level rises by the same ratio as the increase in the quantity
 of money so nothing real changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
classical dichotomy
\series default
, popular with classical thinkers like Hume, says that doubling the money
 supply will double nominal values but not real values.
 
\series bold
Monetary neutrality
\series default
 is the position that changes in the money supply don't affect real variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantity theory of money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It states that increasing the quantity of money eventually increases the
 price level proportionally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
velocity of circulation
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the average number of times a dollar is used (to buy GDP components)
 per year.
 It is by the 
\series bold
equation of exchange
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MV=PY(=\text{nominal GDP})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the price level, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the real GDP, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the quantity of money.
 Expressing this in terms of rates gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Inflation rate}= & \phantom{+}\text{Money growth rate}\\
 & +\text{Rate of velocity change}\\
 & -\text{Real GDP growth rate}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the rate of velocity change is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that inflation is effectively a tax on wealth...
 or at least, that stored as money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Fisher effect
\series default
 is how increasing inflation increases the nominal interest rate by the
 same amount, so the real interest rate on wealth is unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Forex (ch25)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You trade currencies at a 
\series bold
foreign exchange market
\series default
.
 The demand for a currency is influenced by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The exchange rate itself (the more expensive CAD is, the less people want
 it)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected future exchange rate (the 
\series bold
expected profit effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
World demand for Canadian exports (the 
\series bold
exports effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Interest rates for that currency vs.
 others
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The supply for a currency is influenced by basically the same things:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The exchange rate itself
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The expected future exchange rate (the 
\series bold
expected profit effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Our demand for their imports (the 
\series bold
imports effect
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Interest rates for that currency vs.
 others
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand for one currency is supply for another currency.
 When interest rates differ between currencies, there is an 
\series bold
interest rate differential
\series default
 that has the obvious effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Arbitrage 
\series default
is buying low in one market and selling high in another for a certain gain.
 This means the market achieves four outcomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
The law of one price
\series default
: The price of a thing is the same everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
No round-trip profit
\series default
: You can't make money by trading in a cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Interest rate parity
\series default
: The risk free rate is the same for all currencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Purchasing power parity
\series default
: The price of a thing is the same in all currencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Speculation
\series default
 is, to massively generalize, +EV trading with risk.
 Expectations and forecasts create short run exchange rate volatility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
real exchange rate
\series default
 is the relative price of a good between two countries.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{RER}=E\times P/P'
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the nominal exchange rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is our price level, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 is their price level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the short run, a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 causes 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{RER}$
\end_inset

 to change.
 In the long run, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{RER}\times P'/P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exchange rate policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
flexible exchange rate
\series default
 is determined fully by the forex market.
 A 
\series bold
fixed exchange rate
\series default
 is fixed by a government via active intervention, usually by burning their
 foreign reserves or printing money.
 A 
\series bold
crawling peg
\series default
 is a peg that changes over time according to some policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Financing international trade
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A country's 
\series bold
balance of payments accounts
\series default
 records its international trading, borrowing, and lending.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
current accounts balance 
\series default
is exports minus imports plus net interest and net transfers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
capital and financial account
\series default
 is foreign investment in Canada, minus Canadian investment abroad.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
official settlements account
\series default
 is the negative change in 
\series bold
Canadian official reserves
\series default
 (foreign reserves).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global loanable funds market has supply and demand curves much like
 those on the level of a single country.
 These can be used to determine a world interest rate, and domestic borrowers/le
nders can lend internationally to borrow/lend at this rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
net borrower
\series default
 is a country that is borrowing more than it's lending, and a 
\series bold
net lender
\series default
 is not.
 A 
\series bold
debtor nation
\series default
 has borrowed more than it has lent.
 A 
\series bold
creditor nation
\series default
 has not.
 The US and Canada are both debtor nations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the 
\series bold
current account balance
\series default
 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{CAB}=\text{NX}+\text{Net interest income}+\text{Net transfers}
\]

\end_inset

It's mostly net exports.
 The other stuff is tiny.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{BoP}=\text{CA}+\text{KA}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Table 25.2) With 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 exports, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 imports, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 government expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 net taxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 investment, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 savings, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Net exports} & =X-M\\
\text{Government sector surplus} & =T-G\\
\text{Private sector surplus} & =S-I\\
X-M & =(T-G)+(S-I)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

A short term change in the nominal exchange rate doesn't change the real
 exchange rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Aggregate supply & demand (ch26)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aggregate supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Aggregate supply
\series default
 is the relationship between real GDP supplied and the price level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Long run
\series default
: real GDP supplied = potential GDP because an increase in the price level
 is incorporated into both the price of products and the price of factors
 of production.
 So LAS is a vertical line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Short run
\series default
: the price of factors of production and potential GDP remain constant (they
 are sticky).
 Then a rise in the price level increases the real GDP supplied.
 So SAS is an upward sloping line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More aggregate supply if there is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More potential GDP, which happens if there is:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
More labour (full-employment quantity)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More capital (incl.
 human capital)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Better tech
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Lower 
\series bold
money wage rate
\series default
 (in the short run only, because relative prices will catch up)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aggregate demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Aggregate demand
\series default
 is the relationship between real GDP demanded and the price level.
 Slopes downward for two reasons:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Wealth effect
\series default
: People have less real wealth when the price level rises, so people save
 more and spend less.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Substitution effects
\series default
: An increasing price level raises interest rates, which means people wait
 a bit before buying things (
\series bold
intertemporal substitution
\series default
) and buy cheaper things.
 Also, it makes foreign things cheaper (
\series bold
international substitution
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is influenced by three things:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Expectations
\series default
: If people expect to make more later, they buy more now.
 (Whether in wages, interest, or profit.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Fiscal policy
\series default
: Taxes, transfer payments, and government purchases all affect disposable
 income.
 More disposable income means people buy more.
 
\series bold
Monetary policy
\series default
: National bank changing interest rates and quantity of money.
 More money means more aggregate demand because interest rates are lower
 so it's easier to get a loan.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The world economy
\series default
: A weaker domestic currency means we'll export more, so aggregate demand
 increases.
 More foreign income means Canada exports more and aggregate demand increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula was on the blackboard:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{AD}=C+I+G+(X-M)
\]

\end_inset


