\begin_layout Subsection
How aggregate expenditure determines real GDP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
aggregate expenditure curve
\series default
 is aggregate planned expenditure vs.
 real GDP.
 Turns out:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{induced expenditure} & =C-M\\
\text{autonomous expenditure} & =I+G+X
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Planned expenditure is not necessarily actual expenditure, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is maybe not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $C+I+G+X-M$
\end_inset

 here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Equilibrium expenditure
\series default
 is when planned expenditure equals real GDP.
 When actual expenditure doesn't equal planned expenditure, they converge
