es to their target level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The multiplier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
multiplier
\series default
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Multiplier} & =\frac{\Delta\text{equilibrium expenditure}}{\Delta\text{autonomous expenditure}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{MPS}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It gives you how much GDP increases with a given investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Expenditure vs.
 demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the aggregate demand curve slopes down due to the wealth effect
 and the substitution effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When aggregate planned expenditure increases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aggregate expenditure shifts up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aggregate demand shifts right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the short run:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aggregate expenditure increases...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But SAS doesn't change and the price level increases too...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So the increase in aggregate expenditure is a bit cancelled out.
