\begin_layout Section
The business cycle, inflation, and deflation (ch28)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two business cycle theories: mainstream and real.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mainstream business cycle theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This theory says that potential GDP grows at a steady rate, but aggregate
 demand grows at a fluctuating rate.
 If aggregate demand grows slower than potential GDP, then a lower-than-expected
 growth in aggregate demand creates a recessionary gap (other way: inflationary
 gap).
 There are a couple of variations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Keynesian cycle theory
\series default
: Aggregate demand fluctuates mainly because investment fluctuates, driven
 by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

animal spirits
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (confidence).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Monetarist cycle theory
\series default
: Aggregate demand fluctuates mainly because of investment and consumption
 expenditure fluctuate, mainly because the growth rate of the quantity of
 money fluctuates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
New classical cycle theory
\series default
: Money wage rate and SAS are determined by potential GDP and 
\emph on
expected
\emph default
 aggregate demand.
 So only 
\emph on
unexpected
\emph default
 fluctuations in aggregate demand do things.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
New Keynesian cycle theory
\series default
: Money wage rate and SAS were negotiated in the past, so they were determined
 by past rational expectations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Real business cycle theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This theory says that productivity fluctuates because of technological change,
 international disturbances, climate, and natural disasters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Impulses
\series default
 are generated by technology.
 Technology that makes existing capital obsolete temporarily decrease productivi
ty â€” in the loanable funds market, DLF shifts left because firms purchase
 less, and in the labour market, the supply and demand for labour both fall,
 but demand falls more, so the real wage rate falls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RBC theorists also believe that a higher interest rate makes people work
 more, so that they can have more money now.
 Many economists believe this intertemporal substitution effect is small,
 but RBC theorists think it's big.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Criticism of RBC theory include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The money wage rate is clearly sticky.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Intertemporal substitution doesn't account for all the large fluctuations
 in labour supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Productivity shocks may be caused by changes in aggregate demand, not just
 technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standard defenses are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A single theory explains both growth and cycles.
 And it doesn't matter if assumptions are weird as long as the theory works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
RBC is consistent with microeconomic ideas about labour and investment decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inflation cycles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Demand-pull inflation
\series default
 is that which starts because aggregate demand increases (for any reason).
 The initial effect is AD shifting right.
 Then, the money wage rate rises and SAS shifts upward compensate, putting
 us back at LAS.
 If this happens repeatedly (e.g.
 via increasing the money supply), we get inflation.
 This happened in Canada in the late 1960s due to US and Canadian government
 spending.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Cost-push inflation
\series default
 is that which starts with costs increase, whether due to a higher money
 wage rate or a higher price for raw materials.
 This happened in Canada in the mid 1970s when OPEC quadrupled oil prices.
 It is associated with stagflation.
 Mechanism: SAS goes left, then government adds more money and AD goes right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Expected inflation
\series default
 doesn't make real GDP fluctuate because SAS and AD both go up at the same
 rate.
 (More precisely, SAS shifts left because producers expect inflation, and
 AD shifts right because the money wage rate rises.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
rational expectation
\series default
 is the best forecast based on all relevant information and is often wrong,
 thanks economists!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the end, it turns out that faster-than-expected inflation is like demand-pull
 inflation and lower-than-expected inflation is...
 exactly that.
