\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Deflation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One-time falls in the price level can be caused by lower aggregate demand,
 or higher short-run aggregate supply, but this is not deflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deflation is a persistently falling price level, which requires one of the
 above conditions to happen for a long time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantity theory of money gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Inflation rate} & =\text{Money growth rate}\\
 & \phantom{=}+\text{Rate of velocity change}\\
 & \phantom{=}-\text{Real GDP growth rate}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and since deflation is just negative inflation, we can use this to figure
 out the money growth rate at which there is zero inflation.
 Below this, there is deflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since deflation is rare, it is usually unanticipated.
 So it causes some effects, like:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Workers receive more real wage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Employers hire fewer workers, so employment decreases and output falls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Firms invest less and slows potential GDP growth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Low nominal interest rate increases cash holdings and decreases velocity
 of circulation (which can lead to a vicious cycle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deflation is ended by removing its cause.
 You could simply print more money.
\end_layout

